- MK_Editor-core:
  - the kernel(backend) for MK_Editor
  - tui and gui processor
  - supports instances
  - manage/talk to processes
  - manages memory
  - builtin lua scripting and repl
  - can set vars from json
   - source json from lua
  - source from archived dirs
  - compile config into byte code
  - compile config into program w/ cpp in the src/config dir

- Lingo:
  - kernel = the backend
  - distro,editor = the frontend
  - instance = one of the running editors, indexed by creation order
  - runtime = files necessary to run editor
   - mostly consists of base configs, libs, and bins
  - opt = optional
  - Core:
  - Frontend:
    - (major) mode = a layer which doesn't interfere with other layers
     - has it's own tools, config, and keymodes
    - minor mode = an extention to one or more major modes
    -(major) keymode = like major modes, but only for keys
     - it is not required that they are bound to modes
    - minor keymode = an extention to one or more major key modes
    - Key Names:
      - Super = win
      - Meta  = ctrl, cmd
      - Alt   = alt
    - buffer = a buffer of data that the editor manages
     - to edit buffers, you use a translation layer
     - on save, the buffer data is (generally) written to a file
    - translation layer, translator = translates your buffer data between either
     - the buffer and you, or
     - the buffer and the file
    - session = the current instance
    - workspace = a set of windows, aka a "view"
     - each tab holds one workspace
    - <feature>(source) = the lua source for that <feature> is in the runtime dir
    - Package Manager:
      - extension = an extension to a package
       - a package that requires and utilizes another package
      - bundle = multiple packages in one
       - can opt out of packages

- MK_Editor(frontend):
  - usablity of neovim with the functionality of emacs
  - a bare-bones distro for the MK kernel
  - comes with vim-like keybindings and interface
  - has both a tilling and floating window manger
   - tilling wm is the default
  - can utilize env vars
  - themes are defined in lua
  - multi-cursor editing
  - macros
  - can change default directory paths
  - share data between multiple instances
  - UI: (source)
    - the elements that make up your view
    - Status Line:
      - the bar just above the cmd line
      - has support for the tui
    - Status Column:
      - the column of icons/chars before the actual text
  - Modes:
    - define custom modes
    - Defaults:
      - normal, the base mode
      - insert
      - command
      - visual
      - visual-line
      - visual-block
      - terminal
  - Help:
    - has help akin to vim's :help cmd
    - help files support config specific vars like keybinds
    - help files written in markdown
    - can also source/generate help text from the lua source code
    - HelpSite:
      - website to display/translate help files
      - can source from vars json files
  - Dried: (source)
    - the default file manager for the editor
     - dried is a play on emacs's fm, dired
    - can be used stand-alone, like lf, in the terminal
    - supports dired data
  - Terminal:
    - basic terminal for the editor
    - core is builtin, for performance
     - extented functionallity is defined in lua source
    - can utilize many different shells
    - by default, supports
     - the builtin lua repl
     - sh, bash, zsh, fish
     - cmd, powershell, git-bash
  - Sessions: (source)
    - load/save sessions
    - sessions save the state of the current instance
    - store sessions in any config type
     - default = byte code
    - lazily loads workspaces, for better performance
    - Workspaces:
      - load/save workspaces
      - workspaces save the state of the current view
      - save as any config type
       - default = byte code
  - Package Manager: (source)
    - lua library/configs for managing packages
    - Default (pkg)Requirements:
      - provide source code
      - provide description
      - provide version
      - provide docs
      - provide (opt)deps
    - can have custom pkg requirements
    - by default, pkgs that don't meet requirements will have to be forcefully installed
    - package configs are written in lua
    - you can use lua for automation
    - packages can be downloaded from anywhere
    - create (nick)names for sources
     - main = "https://github.com/MKEditor/packages/"
    - the official site supports links to other pkg sites
     - will also host pkgs locally
    - the official site organizes packages like github
     - Name|Organization/pkg_name
    - handles deps
    - download directly as any config type
    - add tags to define package type
     - tags can be custom
    - Bundles:
      - handle multiple packages
      - bundles are generally links to multiple pkgs
       - can also have the "physical" pkgs in the bundle's source
      - by default, choose what packages to download
    - Docs:
      - docs for your package(s)
      - docs are downloaded by default
      - by default, the docs dir is <proj_root>/docs
       - this can be configured to be anywhere
      - docs can be written in any format, since the file viewer is separate
       - markdown is preferred, since it is supported by default
  - LocList:
    - location lists
    - similar to vim's quickfix lists "https://neovim.io/doc/user/quickfix.html"
    - by default, writes to lua file
     - naturally, you can write to any config file type
  - Buffers:
    - the buffer of data that you actually edit
     - this buffer of data is usually copied from a file, and vice versa
    - buffers have a max size limit (which can be modified)
    - buffers usually vary in size (for performance)
    - what you see in the window isn't always the actually data you edit
     - the data goes back and forth through a translation layer
  - Translation Layers:
    - translate buffer data
    - generally, translators go between you and the buffer, for modularity
     - but they can also go between the buffer and the file
    - the default translator doesn't do much
     - in most cases it directly displays the buffer
     - supports
      - folds
      - hidden text (text hidden from the buffer)
      - 
  - Clipper: (source)
    - clipboard manager for the editor
     - clipboards are just special buffers that contain lists of data
    - clipboards are defined by clipper, they aren't a builtin feature
    - file to share clipboards between instances
    - can have as many clipboards as you want
    - Default Clipboards:
      - System:
        - represents the system's clipboard
      - Instance<number>:
        - clipboard for instance<number>
      - Current:
        - is a copy of the clipboard for the current instance
  - DocView: (source)
    - a library for document viewing in the editor
      - like zathura
    - also gives you an abstraction for defining translation layers
    - Markdown:
      - a doc viewer extention for viewing md files
      - supports the help style markdown
    - extentions for viewing and editing docs
  - Language Config: (source)
    - lua library/configs for using languages in the editor
     - also lets other apps get language data
    - the standard for language in your editor
    - supports lsp and dap
    - support for both programming and human languages
    - Linting:
      - api for language linting
      - supports lsp
      - extensions for grammar and spell checking in human languages
    - Completion:
      - api for language completion
      - supports lsp
      - extensions for autocomplete in human languages
      - snippets
    - Highlighting:
      - api for language highlighting
      - supports lsp
      - supports treesitter
    - Formatting:
      - api for language formating among other things
      - extension for visual indent
    - Debugging:
      - api for debugging
      - supports dap
    - Misc:
      - other language specific configs


